0an%20organization%20work%2C%20said%20Kevin%20Groves%2C%20a%20professor%20of%20management%20at%20Pepperdine's%20Graziadio%20Business%20School.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWe're%20preserving%20what's%20most%20important%20to%20us%2C%20while%20recognizing%20our%20environment%20has%20changed%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHere%20are%20three%20pieces%20of%20advice%20on%20taking%20over%20after%20a%20leader%20who%20looms%20large%20%E2%80%94%C2%A0and%20who%20might%20still%20be%20down%20the%20hall.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22041531e3-7e49-4259-b6f6-5fb51d2f80c6%5C%22%3EDon't%20be%20impatient%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EStepping%20into%20this%20position%20successfully%20starts%20with%20indicating%20sincere%20interest%20in%20the%20role%20and%20prioritizing%20what's%20best%20for%20the%20organization%2C%20Nancy%20Ho%2C%20an%20executive%20coach%20based%20in%20Singapore%2C%20told%20BI.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BYou%20cannot%20be%20impatient%20and%20rush%20into%20it.%20It%20should%20not%20be%20seen%20like%20you're%20power-hungry%20or%20claiming%20a%20role%20prematurely%2C%26quot%3B%20Ho%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EInstead%2C%20she%20said%2C%20new%20leaders%20need%20to%20focus%20on%20understanding%20a%20company's%20culture%20and%20how%20they%20can%20position%20themselves%20as%20an%20asset%20to%20the%20organization.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EJames%20Reed%2C%20CEO%20of%20the%20UK-based%20recruitment%20company%20Reed%2C%20said%20there%20is%20no%20harm%20in%20declaring%20to%20your%20boss%20that%20you%20are%20ambitious%20and%20aim%20to%20lead%20an%20organization%2C%20%26quot%3Beven%20if%20you%20avoid%20explicitly%20saying%20you're%20after%20their%20job.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BAsk%20what%20you%20need%20to%20learn%20and%20what%20more%20you%20can%20contribute%20to%20support%20them%2C%26quot%3B%20Reed%20said.%20%26quot%3BThen%20they%20will%20be%20aware%20of%20your%20ambition%20but%20appreciate%20that%20you%20are%20seeking%20to%20help%20and%20learn%20from%20them%20rather%20than%20undermine%20them.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%229cea030b-67ed-4220-a6b8-563a843ae0a3%5C%22%3EDon't%20rock%20the%20boat%20too%20early%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EHo%20said%20it's%20important%20not%20to%20make%20drastic%20changes%20too%20soon%20upon%20getting%20the%20job.%20Ho%20recommended%20that%20the%20first%20step%20is%20acknowledging%20the%20good%20work%20done%20before%20them.%20Then%2C%20they%20should%20gain%20the%20team's%20trust%20by%20carefully%20working%20with%20them%20and%20making%20small%2C%20gradual%20changes%20to%20improve%20the%20organization's%20effectiveness.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWhen%20there's%20a%20certain%20buy-in%2C%20and%20people%20are%20more%20comfortable%20with%20a%20different%20leader%2C%20then%20you%20introduce%20changes%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESabina%20Nawaz%2C%20a%20US-based%20CEO%20coach%2C%20said%20new%20leaders%20should%20not%20make%20changes%20for%20at%20least%20the%20first%20three%20months%20because%20the%20first%20thing%20to%20do%20after%20receiving%20the%20title%20is%20%26quot%3Bto%20be%20curious.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BGo%20on%20a%20listening%20tour%2C%20excavate%20the%20reasons%20behind%20decisions%20or%20actions%2C%20try%20to%20make%20sense%20of%20things%20from%20the%20perspective%20of%20others%3A%20given%20that%20they're%20smart%20and%20well-meaning%2C%20what%20did%20they%20have%20in%20mind%20when%20they%20acted%20this%20way%2C%26quot%3B%20Nawaz%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EChristian%20Tr%C3%B6ster%2C%20a%20professor%20of%20leadership%20and%20organizational%20behavior%20at%20Germany's%20K%C3%BChne%20Logistics%20University%2C%20told%20BI%20that%20new%20leaders%20can%20demonstrate%20they're%20becoming%20part%20of%20the%20organization%20by%20being%20careful%20not%20to%20suggest%20that%20everything%20should%20change.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BBecause%20then%20you're%20showing%20that%20you%20are%20not%20like%20them%2C%20that%20you%20cannot%20be%20trusted%2C%26quot%3B%20Tr%C3%B6ster%20said.%20%26quot%3BThen%20you%20don't%20have%20the%20commitment%20of%20your%20employees%20to%20actually%20go%20with%20you.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETr%C3%B6ster%20said%20that%20when%20an%20incoming%20leader%20would%20have%20to%20report%20to%20the%20person%20who%20held%20the%20post%20in%20the%20past%2C%20it's%20important%20to%20have%20a%20conversation%20about%20expectations.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHe%20said%20that%20while%20org%20charts%20are%20often%20clear%2C%20layers%20are%20often%20not%20always%20evident%2C%20including%20what%20relationships%20people%20have%20and%20who%20they%20tend%20to%20go%20to%20for%20advice.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BI%20would%20try%20to%20make%20that%20visible%2C%26quot%3B%20Tr%C3%B6ster%20said.%20That%20way%2C%20he%20said%2C%20workers%20know%20who%20they're%20expected%20to%20go%20to%20and%20leaders%20and%20employees%20can%20agree%20to%20the%20arrangement.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%20data-toc-id%3D%5C%22caa3a6aa-1c68-4593-9552-f5c01b2f9a6d%5C%22%3EDon't%20be%20afraid%20to%20be%20different%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20those%3Cstrong%3E%20%3C%2Fstrong%3Etaking%20over%20a%20new%20role%20while%20their%20predecessor%20is%20still%20around%20%E2%80%94%20especially%20someone%20as%20%26quot%3Bestablished%20and%20admired%26quot%3B%20as%20Anna%20Wintour%2C%20it's%20important%20to%20take%20advantage%20of%20your%20access%20to%20them%2C%20Amanda%20Augustine%2C%20a%20career%20coach%20at%20resume.io%2C%20told%20BI%20via%20email.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BStart%20the%20job%20as%20a%20sponge%2C%20learning%20what%20you%20can%20from%20your%20predecessor%20and%20other%20colleagues%2C%26quot%3B%20she%20said%2C%20adding%20that%20it's%20important%20not%20to%20stay%20in%20information-gathering%20mode%20forever.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EJochen%20Menges%2C%20a%20professor%20of%20leadership%20at%20the%20University%20of%20Zurich%20and%20the%20University%20of%20Cambridge%2C%20told%20BI%20that%20new%20leaders%20should%20%26quot%3Bbe%20different%26quot%3B%20and%20avoid%20trying%20to%20replicate%20the%20exact%20leadership%20style%20or%20strategy%20of%20the%20person%20they're%20replacing.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIf%20they're%20too%20close%2C%20then%20they'll%20seem%20to%20be%20a%20copy%2C%20and%20then%20they%20can%20never%20live%20up%2C%26quot%3B%20he%20said.%20When%20new%20bosses%20are%20different%20in%20some%20ways%2C%20Menges%20said%2C%20they%20can%20be%20%26quot%3Ba%20leader%20in%20their%20own%20right.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fcareer-coaches-anna-wintour-vogue-2025-6%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1751102701000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F685e520d85e81483682ce25d%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fcareer-coaches-anna-wintour-vogue-2025-6%22%2C%22summary%22%3A%22Wintour%20announced%20that%20Vogue%20will%20hire%20a%20US%20head%20of%20editorial%20content.%20People%20coming%20into%20a%20high-profile%20roles%20need%20to%20be%20strategic%2C%20experts%20said.%22%2C%22author%22%3A%22abharade%40insider.com%20(Aditi%20Bharade%2CTim%20Paradis%2CLindsay%20Dodgson)%22%2C%22engagement%22%3A73%2C%22canonicalUrl%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fcareer-coaches-anna-wintour-vogue-2025-6%22%2C%22cdnAmpUrl%22%3A%22%22%2C%22ampUrl%22%3A%22%22%7D%2C%7B%22title%22%3A%22Here%20are%20the%204%20home%20trends%20that%20are%20hot%20in%202025%22%2C%22content%22%3A%22%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%227008%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Two%20women%20and%20a%20man%20are%20walking%20toward%20a%20white%20house.%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F685aeaa685e81483682cad14%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%224672%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EA%20survey%20from%20the%20National%20Association%20of%20Home%20Builders%20reveals%20what%20today's%20buyers%20value%20most%20in%20a%20home.%3Cp%3EJackyenjoyphotography%2FGetty%20Images%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E